See #65 for the prior discussion on the removal of the id parameter from CredentialRequest.

My interpretation of the `LookupUserRecord(request.id)` portion is that it is meant for the wrapper protocol to perform the lookup, so that those details are not kept as part of the OPAQUE protocol.

@chris-wood Thoughts on this / perhaps editing the text to make it more clear that OPAQUE doesn't handle lookup and doesn't manage the id in its CredentialRequest message?

Somewhat unrelated question, but:

Should this specification define a format for the serialized version of the "finalized object" containing (envU, pkS, skS, pkU, kU)? Something like:
```
CredentialRecord {
  opaque envU<1..2^16-1>;
  opaque kU<1..2^16-1>;
  opaque pkU<1..2^16-1>;
}
```

And actually pkS does not need to be stored here, because it is already a part of the credentials object, via:

"Applications MUST include skU in secret_credentials and pkS in either cleartext_credentials or secret_credentials."

And we likely do not want to advocate for storing skS somewhere like this, so we can retain/amend the comment:

"If skS and pkS are used for multiple users, the server can store these values separately and omit them from the user's record."

> what is a wrapper protocol expected to do with envU, kU, pkU other than treat them as raw bytestrings that should be serialized in some format?

If these were serialized and minted by implementation A, then implementation A would presumably know how to parse them. I think this is useful only if, for example, implementation A mints the records and implementation B consumes them. I could see that happening in practice if, e.g., the registration and login phases were two separate processes running different implementations, wherein the registration process minted CredentialRecords and then the login process consumed them. If you think arrangements like this are likely, I see no harm in adding something like CredentialRecord.

As for serialization: yes, we should definitely version them. I'd just stick in the same version used for the protocol version, e.g.:

~~~
struct {
   uint16 version;
   uint16 length;
   select (0xff00) { // version 00 for the draft, or whatever
      // information about the configuration, e.g., OPRF suite and so on, since that determines kU's encoding 
      Envelope envU;
      Scalar kU;
      opaque pkU<0..2^16-1>;
   }
} CredentialRecord;
~~~

